I'm a pretty picky eater and Mediterranean food is typically a no-go for me due to an issue with cilantro that taints everything it touches. But I absolutely love Roti. I imagine connoisseurs of Mediterranean would say that Roti qualifies in the same way that Taco Bell qualifies as Mexican food, but I think that's what works for me. But don't interpret that to mean that the quality of Roti's food is comparable to Taco Bell, it's much, much better.  My usual order is the chicken roti on a rice plate with cous cous and garlic sauce. The chicken roti is absolutely delectable, while the steak is a great choice too, and the chicken kabob a solid third place. The meals are plentiful but don't leave you feeling awful like most other fast food places.  The other great thing about Roti, this location included, is that the service is always super efficient and generous. The only knock against this location is that it's a pretty tight fit, especially if you're trying to squeeze in a toddler, a stroller, and a high chair. But it's a small complaint and we always make it work.

I have been here a few times and although the food is good, it's not worth the hassle. Some of the employees have terrible attitudes. They don't greet you when you walk in and when you ask them for something, they act like it's a chore - newsflash, you're getting paid to provide a service. I walked in at 7:07pm tonight, nearly a full two hours before closing. The falafel was dry and cracked (but they tried to tell me it was fresh), and the meat was cold. The chicken kabob meat in my pita was stone cold...um, hello, safe food temperatures anyone? They start to break down the line hours before closing. It's ridiculous. Half of the time you can't see the veggies and toppings because they're cleaning the line so they can go home. The last person in the store pays the same as the first person and should get the same experience. Overall, I would skip this location unless you don't want fresh food or a pleasant experience.
